General von Goler explains the Roman works as follows: “ A dike was extended along each side of the isthmus in the direction of the town. While these were building, of course with each rise of the tide the space within would be overflowed. When the dikes were nearly completed, the Romans waited until the ebb had carried off the water, and then rapidly pushed their works to completion before the next turn of the tide. Thus the sea was shut out and the isthmus left dry. Meanwhile the dikes them- selveS‚ being raised to the height of the waIIS, each served the purpose of an agger for approach to the town.'’
